AB  - This paper argues that it is crucial to take account of both home and host country contexts in order, adequately, to understand their implications for Chinese enterprises investing into foreign countries. This calls for an analysis that is sensitive to both home and host country contexts, and that takes into account how the institutions and political systems in those contexts establish institutional and resource capital needs for the overseas-investing firm. We discuss and illustrate three different combinations of Chinese and host country characteristics, and the firm-level learning and adaptation required in the light of the relevant capitals likely to be available to Chinese firms. The analysis draws upon insights from resource-based, institutional, and political perspectives. While it is developed with specific reference to China, we also suggest that this form of analysis can be applied more generally to the implementation of outward foreign direct investment from any country. 本文认为，同时考虑原籍国和东道国的情境对中国在外投资企业的影响是至关重要的。这就呼吁一种对原籍国和东道国的情境都很敏感的分析，这种分析考虑在那些情境下制度和政治体系如何建立海外投资企业所需要的制度和资源资本。我们探讨和展示了三种不同的中国和东道国特点的组合，以及中国企业现有的、相关资本要求的企业层次的学习和适应。这个分析基于资源依赖、制度的和政治的视角。虽然它是以中国为具体的参照而建立起来的，但我们也认为这种形式的分析能够被更广泛地用于任何国家的海外直接投资企业的实施。 The rapid expansion of outward foreign direct investment (OFDI) from China has been a new and significant development in international business during the past decade. The rise in China's OFDI was particularly marked after 2005 as its ‘go global’ strategy was consolidated and government restrictions were progressively eased to ensure political support for OFDI (Salidjanova, 2011). The China Investment Corporation was founded in 2007 as China's first sovereign wealth fund, to promote profitable overseas investments as an alternative to holding foreign currency reserves in low-yield US bonds. China's OFDI expanded from an annual flow of under US$100 million in the 1980s to approximately US$10 billion by 2005, surging to US$84 billion by 2012 (UNCTAD, 2013). Even in 2010, when global OFDI levels fell dramatically as a result of the financial crisis, Chinese non-financial OFDI recorded a year-on-year increase of 25.9 percent. It represented 5.1 percent of global OFDI flows placing the country as the fifth largest provider of OFDI in the world (Ministry of Commerce, 2011; Peoples' Bank of China, 2011; The Heritage Foundation, 2012). By 2012 Chinese OFDI stock had reached an estimated US$509 billion (UNCTAD, 2013). The marked increase in China's OFDI has understandably attracted growing attention among both academics and politicians. It raises a number of important theoretical and policy issues (Alon, Child, Li, & McIntyre, 2011). To date, more attention has been given to the motives behind Chinese OFDI than to how it is negotiated and implemented in different host country contexts (e.g., Buckley, Clegg, Cross, Xin, Voss, & Zheng, 2007; The Economist, 2013). China has been seen to qualify, even challenge, the conventional analysis that the internationalization of firms is motivated by opportunities to capitalize on ownership, location, and internalization (OLI) advantages. It has been asked whether we need an alternative analysis that is better suited to emerging economies in which firms may not possess such advantages (Boston Consulting Group, 2011; Child & Rodrigues, 2005; Dunning, 2006; Marinov & Marinova, 2011; Mathews, 2006; Narula, 2006; Ramamurti & Singh, 2009; Rugman, 2009). One reason why China can be regarded as a different case concerns the suspicion that the motives for its overseas investment are informed by a political agenda. The heavy state guidance of much Chinese OFDI suggests that it is an orchestrated arm of the country's foreign policy, motivated by the country's strategic interests (Luo, Xue, & Han, 2010; Zhang, Zhou, & Ebbers, 2010). The assumption that this is the case has led to opposition to Chinese acquisitions in Australia and the US (Hanemann & Rosen, 2011; Scott, 2009) and to debate over the motives for, and impact of, Chinese investment in sub-Saharan Africa (Brautigam, 2010; Van Dijk, 2009). this the motives for Chinese OFDI to both its home and host country It is the of, and for, this paper that it is crucial to take account of both home and host country contexts in to understand their implications for Chinese enterprises investing into foreign countries. The to which the internationalization of Chinese firms has been by support from their home as as their to to in their host contexts, attention than It is to a that this analysis and also to how it can of the advantages and Chinese OFDI as as the that foreign investing Chinese firms may to We that such a for OFDI from emerging economies by government are to this and rise to the that The first is for a more of than has generally been in international business The of home and host country contexts relevant to internationalization need to be a more of a needs to be to the in the & Rodrigues, 2010). This the of institutional and political of country It of the of business systems in different much international business business and the and the country levels of This is in a such as China, on to the largest The of the Chinese state in internationalization policy, and its can to on host country for Chinese firms of a that be to countries. can host country and firms from and and the institutional and political of country a is that account be of both home and host country contexts attention to the implications of different combinations of the that are by in host country While attention has been given to the the home and host we the implications for foreign of specific combinations of home and host country contexts & 2012). It is the of home and host advantages and and that the under which firms & Li, the and that are available in their and host contexts as as the institutional capital available to the firms. is to an of the to the resource capital and institutional capital required for OFDI in a of hom