AB  - We examine the relationship between corporate social responsibility (CSR) reporting and corporate social performance (CSP) of emerging market multinational enterprises (EMMNEs). Drawing on neo-institutional theory, we predict that EMMNE CSR reporting positively affects their CSP because it increases global legitimacy pressures on these firms to be substantively socially responsible, and improves managerial awareness of their social and environmental impacts and potential solutions to manage them. We also predict that pervasiveness of home country institutional voids weakens this effect by constraining EMMNEs’ learning opportunities. Finally, we predict that internationalization and listings on developed country stock exchanges magnify the relationship between CSR reporting and CSP by intensifying global legitimacy pressures for substantive CSR. Most of our hypotheses are supported in a longitudinal study of 93 of the largest EMMNES ranked by the United Nations Conference on Trade and Development between 2005 and 2012.
