AB  - The British Journal of Management is celebrating its 25th anniversary this year, and soon I will be celebrating 27 years as a management professor at IESE Business School. This is close enough in time to consider the changes and evolution of my school, and to reflect that they are representative of the changes management education has suffered in Europe. My relationship with IESE goes further back in time. Still at engineering school (1977), I started working as research assistant for my mentor, Professor Josep Riverola, now Emeritus Professor at IESE. My job was to take care of the computer centre, which then housed a single computer with 32 kbytes of memory and which served five terminals around the school, as well as to develop some programs and teaching materials for operations research. I graduated shortly afterwards, and then worked for my doctoral degree in engineering and my PhD in managerial economics and decision sciences at Northwestern University. I went back to IESE in 1984 as a professor. The school was quite different back then, essentially in two important dimensions: internationalization and research. Let me deal with each one at a time. One can truly say that IESE was always an international business school. In fact, the Spanish language helped us to reach other parts of the world very early on, but we still had to wait a few years to see a real push in this direction. Twenty-five years later, English now dominates; the full-time MBA, the Global Executive MBA and the Doctoral Programme are all totally international in any sense you can consider: participants, faculty, delivery language, content and so on. But this is also true of the overall aspects of the school and even in executive education, despite a very large offering in Spanish. All leading business schools in Europe, at different speeds and to different degrees, have internationalized their operations. MBA students and faculty search for international environments, and local products are reduced to the otherwise quite popular product of Executive MBA – and even in this format, internationalization is a positive value from the participants' point of view. In a world rapidly globalizing in many aspects, training future leaders requires a very international context and perspective. In my early years, 25 years ago, internationalization meant visiting the USA from time to time and importing and translating some of the management ideas generated there. Countries such as Spain were eager for such advances. However, European business schools embraced internationalization faster and deeper than the very successful US schools which benefited from a very large local market. Internationalization started early in Europe because country sizes were not big enough to sustain a leading business school. As a consequence, today's leading European schools rate better in some internationalization dimensions – such as student mix, faculty mix, multiple campus – than their corresponding American partners, but perceptions take a long time to change and Europe has not yet exploited this incredible advantage to its full potential. Research took longer to develop. Of course, we always had good representations of excellent European research, even in business schools, but the dominant model was either as part of a university, more focused on teaching and local influence, or as a real business orientation where professors' careers were a mixture of teaching and consulting. IESE is an example of the latter. The implicit contract with faculty members was a given level of quite underpaid teaching that, especially through executive education, opened the door to lucrative consulting, and this generated additional experience, knowledge and ideas that faculty members brought rapidly to class, thus increasing their impact and therefore the chances to get hired again … and so on in a virtuous cycle. The environment helped, as we were still in the infancy of management consulting (more so in Spain than some other countries) and there was therefore very little professional competition. The net result, in addition to the powerful virtuous cycle previously mentioned, was a very well-oiled business model. But even then, internationalization meant a change was required in this model. The mostly local consulting opportunities did not provide much relevant knowledge for international teaching. And, conversely, while teaching in an international programme required more than local experience, it also did not translate easily to consulting activities because even the ‘local cosmopolitan’ was reaching for global services. The consulting industry was maturing, and the virtuous cycle was becoming endangered. Schools made efforts to restore the virtuous cycle in different ways. Some started paying extra for such activities, whilst others started leveraging the prestige that faculty was gaining in international activities. But the tension was already there: the old model was dying and the new one was still unclear. The final nail in the old model's coffin was the increasing importance of research: international faculty wanted to do it, and in fact needed to do it in order to maintain their high value in international markets. The old contract was now broken, at least for some of the faculty. A new contract called for more time for research and much less dedication to external activities such as consulting, which also meant better pay was required to compensate. Schools had to grow fast to pay for the extra expenses and attract good faculty. A new competition was and still is going on: a competition for talent, for faculty members who excel not just in teaching but also in research. In this new move, the dominant standard was established by the USA, developed in a very different context. While Europe was worried about diversity and relevance, the USA had a more scientific approach based on research universities with very large endowments and where teaching was less important. The clear dominance of the American research universities, together with the EU integration process that stirred the whole European educational system, helped to increase the influence of the USA in Europe. Europe, instead of trying to develop its own advantages, tried to compete with the USA in a set of standards where winning was very difficult, at least in a business school context. Of course, there are good reasons behind this imitative behaviour: nobody knows how to measure performance in research, so the only way to win is to follow legitimate models. In addition, the Marshal Plan imported other institutional factors after the Second World War (Djelic, 1998). By following the USA's legitimate and dominant model, business schools decoupled their core operations (teaching) from the nuisance (research) to which they mainly pay lip service. That said, of course, even empty promises drive behaviour and improve research output.1 One thing seems clear: the old contract that worked so well for European schools in the past is now broken. This comes as no surprise: the world changed and business school education had to change, too. Finally, and I will say irreversibly, it has embraced internationalization and research, but no clear model has emerged yet. All these changes took place very quickly and in years of high growth and a generally good economic environment – maybe even too good, as some bubbles were built in, but this provided the funds to fill holes and attract faculty. Is there a new business model for business schools in Europe? Or are they very different ones? Strategy tells us that the best recommendation for any leading business school is to find its own way, and I am sure each school is struggling to find the right answer. Differences are already clear in the international dimension and maybe less so in the research one; it might well be that it is more difficult on this front. Offering international programmes is no longer a differentiator; it is just a reality for all schools. Something more is needed. Some schools have chosen to develop strategic alliances in different parts of the world, some are opening multiple campuses, and some are doing both. IESE in particular has developed a strong network of independent schools created with its support. This network and the two global campuses of Barcelona and Madrid have given the school a very good international profile. IESE has recently added campuses under the IESE name in Sao Paulo and New York, and another soon in Munich, as well as reinforcing the network in Asia and Africa. In addition, most schools are considering how to develop the globalization dimension in all their programmes. Globalization means more than a common language, it means more than debating cases from different contexts, it means more than using the diversity of views in an international class. It means more – but we do not know exactly what should be the right content and methodology. We at IESE are developing a new compulsory first year MBA course under the leadership of Professor Ghemawat, who is trying to provide a unique answer to these difficult questions (Ghemawat, 2011). In addition, all our MBA programmes –executive, global or full-time – are using our different campuses to their benefit. In any case, we are still struggling to define the right business model in this important dimension. Twenty-five years of internationalization and the process is more open than ever. The current economic crisis has accelerated some of the trends. It is very obvious today that the world moves at two different speeds. Developed countries' growth is typically small and many are still struggling to solve the big imbalances from the past, while emerging economies are growing much more rapidly and increasing their influence on the world. In the near future, the majority of MBA graduates and demand will come from emerging economies where most of the action is today taking place. Will they be willing to attend schools in our developed world locations? Or conversely, will students from developed countries look for exposure to emerging economies? What will European schools do? One can expect a new string of changes in the international dimensions of schools. And we all know that big changes mean big opportunities. Who is better positioned to reap the rewards? As a strong believer in Europe, I do hope that this time Europe moves quickly to help emerging economies and, in the process, establishes its world leadership in management education. But action is needed now if we do not want to lose the race again. And the debate is still even more open on the research front. Again we may learn something from the financial and economic crisis. Some authors claim it is a crisis of values, some others claim it is crisis of capitalism, and some even blame business school education; all of them complain that our research was not very helpful in the crisis, in anticipating it, avoiding it or solving its consequences. I think that blaming business schools is an overstatement. On the one hand, I do not think the banking and real estate sectors, the key responsible parties in the crisis, were really following what we preach.2 Furthermore, some literature such as Arruñada and Vázquez (2009) shows that students exposed to management theories are more likely to cooperate than students exposed only to economic theories because ‘human assumptions used in management theories, because of their diverse, implicit and even contradictory nature, do not conflict with the innate set of cooperative tools and may provide a good training ground for such tools’.3 Also Lazzarini, Islam and Mesquita (2009) show that practising managers hold more complex assumptions on human nature than economics would expect (and this mix is good). The arguments, and so the responsibility for the crisis, is more associated with economic and finance models (see Fox, 2009; Lounsbury and Hirsch, 2010). Even if business schools take a part of the blame for the crisis, it is still true that the model of the firm underlying economics and finance has a lot of influence in business schools. Therefore, it is clear to me that we need to rethink our basic paradigms and, in doing so, get back to a more philosophically grounded, humanistic view of management. On the strategy front we see a re-emergence of broader views such as stakeholder theory, sustainability concepts, or Porter and Kramer's (2011) new ‘shared value’ view. Overall, we need to move from an economic perspective of shareholder value creation to a broader concept of stakeholders' value creation and shared capture. It is illustrative that in a panel celebrating 25 years of the Strategic Management Society (SMS) the only point common to all speakers was the recognition that strategy concepts have been dehumanized and too focused on economics. Mainstream research has not been, in general, humanistic enough because it follows economic tradition too much, and because – in an effort to be scientific – it is not getting close enough to the phenomenon it tries to understand, i.e. it is not sufficiently empirical or evidence based as Pfeffer and Sutton (2006) claim it should be. We use the term ‘humanizing’ to indicate a move away from these two pillars. As strategy, management in general needs to be humanized. I do not want to debate here about the realities of management practice in this dimension. It is management research that needs to be humanized (and that is our focus here). To achieve this, we need to concentrate on the basics again. We need to rethink models of the firm with a new perspective. Some initiatives are already going on in this direction. At IESE this year we are holding the Second International Conference on Humanizing Management and the Firm with a special focus this year on the new models of the firm. Similar initiatives are taking place in other venues. In fact, just a few weeks before this IESE will be hosting the First Interdisciplinary Conference on Stakeholders, Resources and Value Creation organized by the European Institute for Advanced Studies in Management (EIASM) and the Strategic Management Society (SMS). There are many different fronts open, and Europe clearly has a head start. Europe may be well placed to restore a value-based view of management and strategy. On the one hand, Europe is not yet completely sold on an ideological view of markets that inhibits any discussion of alternative forms of governance and production. Therefore the ideological barrier is less relevant. Furthermore, Europe might be in a better place to tackle problems associated with political economy, including political strategies (non-market strategies in the USA) or sustainable strategies, of course without neglecting the powerful role of financial markets. Fewer barriers and broader perspectives can help in the difficult way ahead. However, once again we risk losing the race because, at least so far, many of our responses imitate the US response. Instead, we should go back to the philosophical and sociological roots of European management and build an alternative view of what kind of management research is needed (this should not be interpreted as isolationism, which is the best way to kill good research). Europe should be committed to competing within the existing structure of academics and disciplinary forces. We just need to be good enough to attract the interest of the rest of the world. Leading European business schools are developing their vision and strategies for internationalization and research which can provide value and wisdom in the complex world of this century. We have a big challenge ahead but, as noted in this short paper, Europe is well positioned to develop the theoretical foundations for the responsible global corporation in the 21st century.4 At the turn of this century, EIASM promoted in Europe the creation of the European Academy of Management (EURAM). In ten years of debate EURAM has focused on creating a different environment for a different type of research: a European perspective – no less rigorous, just as excellent, but different. EURAM has been a big success. It has grown and consolidated to become one of the key international conferences, and has broadened its reach to doctoral activities, programmes for research directors, knowledge sharing etc. However, there is still more work to be done, helping European management schools and departments develop the right research agenda for their future role as leading management educators. In addition, European schools should also be active in current global initiatives. Recently, the SMS led the launch of the Strategy Research Foundation, an independent entity focused on developing new, innovative, ground-breaking research in the strategy field. A clear goal of this new initiative is to catalyse research that would otherwise be difficult for research institutions to undertake alone. It tries to create networks of research in key issues of strategic management. As a management scholar very involved in both EURAM and the SMS, I hope European schools are able to reach out to these associations and contribute to them, and, in doing so, learn from this interaction and develop their own, unique, particular perspective on the important issues of internationalization and research. Joan E. Ricart, Past-President of the SMS, is the Carl Schrøder Professor of Strategic Management and Chairman of the Strategic Management Department at the IESE Business School, University of Navarra. He is Associate Director for Faculty and Research, and he has been the Director of the Doctoral Program (1995–2006) and Associate Dean for Research (2001–2006). He is also Vice-President of the Iberoamerican Academy of Management. He was the Founding President of the European Academy of Management (2001–2006). He has published several books and papers in leading journals such as the Strategic Management Journal, Harvard Business Review, Journal of International Business Studies, Econometrica and Quarterly Journal of Economics.
