AB  - This article tests the contingency model hypothesis that the international rate of growth of SMEs depends on the effects of entry mode and environmental factors. Principal concepts in the framework are foreign market entry mode, domestic environmental factors, and foreign environmental factors.The internationalization of small- and medium-sized enterprises (SMEs) has become an important issue with the trend moving more toward economic globalization. Research on the performance success of entry strategies into foreign markets has usually been considered from the point of view of multinational corporations. Archival data were collected on 123 publicly held U.S. manufacturing SMEs and subjected to hierarchical regression analysis.Results indicate that firms will have a higher rate of international revenue growth using no-equity-based foreign market entry modes in growing domestic environments. Equity-based modes will produce higher international revenue growth when foreign market risks are high. The findings will give SME managers contextual evidence for making success decisions about entry into foreign markets. (TNM)
