AB  - Thomas Jefferson once reflected that ‘the past is prologue’, so to understand the current state and future development of management research in the UK we have to briefly explore its origins. The academic field of management in UK higher education has a very recent history, in contrast with many other academic disciplines. Indeed, the first academic presence of management in the UK was only in l917, at the seat of the industrial revolution, Manchester. The Manchester Mechanics Institution established the Department of Industrial Administration, whose role was specifically to train engineers and scientists for potential future managerial roles, with little if any research infrastructure or strategy. This Institute metamorphosed into the University of Manchester Institute of Science and Technology in 1966 (as an autonomous body but also as a Faculty of the University of Manchester), at around the same time as the Foundation of Management Education was established to create two UK centres of excellence in management education, the London Business School and the Manchester Business School – both created through private sector funding in 1964. From 1964 onwards, the number and range of academic development in the management sciences escalated to the point that by the 2009 Research Assessment Exercise (RAE) there were over 100 business and management schools in higher education institutes, producing thousands of undergraduates, MBAs and PhDs. The field went through what Preston and Post (1974) described as the three stages of managerial development, which they referred to as the ‘three managerial revolutions’. The first managerial revolution was the appearance of management itself as a specialized function within hierarchical organizations. The second revolution, ‘professionalization’, was encouraged by the growth in industrial organizations and the complexity of managerial tasks. The third, ‘participation’, was ‘the inclusion of persons and groups involved and concerned with the diverse outcomes of managerial activity as participants in the managerial process’. It is this third revolution that led to the importance of research, particularly in systematically evaluating what worked and what did not work in this managerial process. There has been a longer history of research in a limited number of subjects allied and/or integral to management, such as economics, finance, occupational psychology, operational research and the like, but as new functional areas of interest emerged in management (i.e. marketing, human resource management), research was given a new impetus, stimulating interdisciplinary work between disciplines and functions within management and between the management sciences and other social science disciplines. But the real sea change occurred with the advent of the first RAE in the 1980s. This process of rewarding universities for research output directly had the effect of encouraging universities to recruit and develop their researchers, and in the naturally competitive world of business schools it had an even more profound impact of galvanizing researchers to publish their work in the best international journals. There were not only the individual incentives in terms of career advancement through their research output, but also by enhancing their research portfolio it allowed them to be more attractive to higher rated business schools and/or universities – it gave them, in essence, greater career mobility. From the mid-1980s until the last RAE in 2009, the quantity and quality of research did improve enormously, with many British management academics now publishing in more highly ranked international journals and working more collaboratively with academics from other countries. I was fortunate enough to be a member of the RAE panel in management and business in 1991, and then Chair of this panel in 1996 and 2001. I could see how incentive-based approaches, like the RAE in the UK, could motivate both business schools and their academics to invest more effort in applying for research grants, working collaboratively with colleagues on communal research projects, taking greater risks in publishing in more highly rated journals, attending more high profile international conferences (e.g. Academy of Management annual conference) and advancing their special research interests in the wider global community. By the 2001 RAE in the UK, however, the research culture had been changed so dramatically that ‘the research ethic’ was now embedded in the psyche of management researchers, no longer needing the incentives of an RAE that in earlier years stimulated aspiring researchers. Indeed, by 2001 and beyond, game theory overtook the more positive aspects of the RAE, as universities tried to find ways of manufacturing good results (by the proportion of research active staff they put in, by creating joint authorships which were in name only etc.). So the RAE had achieved its goals by the turn of the millennium and in my view no longer served any useful purpose, even in equitably distributing government research funding for the higher education sector (with the science and technology subjects getting a disproportionate allocation compared with the social sciences, the arts and humanities). So the good news is that the UK's research base in the various management disciplines is vibrant, and now part of the DNA of management and business school academics. So, what research is taking place and being published in the UK, and has this changed over the last couple of decades? I tentatively explored this by looking at the output of the British Journal of Management (BJM) from 1990 to 1995 and comparing it with papers published in 2005–2010. I did a rough categorization of papers into a number of different functional areas like ‘marketing’ or ‘organizational behaviour’ etc.; or by research topics like ‘mergers and acquisitions’, ‘training and development’, ‘strategic change’ etc. It was interesting to note that at the beginning of the life of BJM there were a large number of papers that were in ‘the disciplines’ that make up management, particularly marketing, macro organizational behaviour, operations management, accounting and strategy, as opposed to research topic based papers. Incidentally, this was very different from the papers that appeared in the Academy of Management journals of the time, which tended to include papers on organizational behaviour, strategy, management learning etc. but rarely included papers in disciplines outside of organizational behaviour, strategy, human resource management etc., such are marketing, accounting and operations management. Where there were papers in BJM on specific topic areas (illustrated by the titles of some of the BJM papers below), they were in mergers and acquisitions (e.g. ‘The impact of mergers and acquisitions on people at work’), strategic change (e.g. ‘Patterns of strategic change in the development of human resource management’) and management training and development (e.g. ‘Managing as a performing art’), with a smaller number on gender (e.g. ‘Men managers and women workers: women employees as an under-used resource’), organizational psychology or micro-organizational behaviour (e.g. ‘The content of the psychological contract’), entrepreneurship (e g. ‘What does it mean to be enterprising’) and others in the general management arena (e.g. ‘What is happening to middle management’). When we look at the most recent five-year period, from 2005 to 2010, we notice a decline in published papers in some of the disciplines of the earlier years, particularly marketing, accounting, operations management and macro-organizational behaviour, which may indicate the influence of the Academy of Management and/or the internationalization of BJM and/or the editor of the journal during these different sampling periods. I suspect it is basically about the maturity of the academic field, as well as its international orientation, which have broadened the discipline base of published papers. We now see a wider distribution of disciplines from human resource management to micro-organizational behaviour to public sector management to organizational theory, as well as the fields that were more prominent over 20 years ago but less visibly dominating the journal pages. When it comes to the specific topics of interest, once again there is a more even distribution of subject areas, but with interest still in mergers and acquisition, strategic change and change management and gender, but with a more expansive portfolio of topics (illustrated by some of the titles of papers in that topic area) such as cross-cultural issues (e.g. ‘Promotability of host-country nationals: a cross-cultural study’), ethics (e.g. ‘Business ethics as practice’), top management (e.g. ‘Top management, team heterogeneity, strategic change and operational performance’), corporate reputation (e.g. ‘Examining the antecedents and consequences of corporate reputation: a customer perspective’), corporate social responsibility (e.g. ‘Employee volunteering and social capital: contributions to corporate social responsibility), knowledge networks (‘The role of non-structural and informal mechanisms of integration and coordination as forces in knowledge creation’) and innovation (e.g. ‘How innovative are UK firms’) but the most surprising significant addition to the literature, but probably in retrospect in reality the least surprising, was the large number of published studies on leadership (Avolio, Walumbwa and Weber, 2009). This was the single largest category of specific research topic areas, but it was also frequently linked to one of the other issues above, as illustrated by papers entitled ‘Phases of the adoption of innovation in organizations: effects of environment, organization and top managers’ or ‘Leadership and effectiveness in the context of gender: the role of leaders’ verbal behaviour’ etc. Leadership, at all levels in an organization, is an important aspect of achieving any of the above, whether in terms of ethics or corporate reputation or corporate social responsibility (Rothstein and Burke, 2010). Also, given the economic downturn and recession, the issue of leadership has come to the fore, particularly in the finance sector, the lack of leadership in managing risk and growth and the need for a different management style as we enter ‘recession recovery’ mode. As Gadman and Cooper (2009) suggest the leadership challenge is that in this era of overwhelming complexity and ambiguity, contemporary leadership practices are failing to respond to this new world order because they are based on outdated assumptions about the way the world works. These tenets, which emphasize ‘power over and control of’ people, have outlived their usefulness. To seize today's rich patterns of opportunities, we need trust and openness, shared information, clusters of capabilities and a focus on teaming these capabilities through creative leadership. For me it is really heartening to see topics emerging from the literature which have real meaning for the times we live in. The management research community are more and more concerned about leadership; about how we can use the knowledge base and technology we have to improve performance and get better work–life balance; about innovation and creativity; about ethics, given Enron, the expenses debacle of UK politicians and the like; about how we manage effectively strategic change, whilst minimizing its impact on the health and well-being of employees; and about what we all need to do to give back to the community through corporate social responsibility and sustainability more generally. This trend may be partly a result of the importance of ‘research impact’, and its implications for future management research funding, but I would like to think that business school academics see the significance of making their work relevant, whether it is in theory-building or in their empirical investigations, because they have become more interested in the implications of their work for policy making and ultimately seeing their work translated into strategic and significant effective change (Cooper and Starkey, 2010). Much of what is done in the name of management research can positively contribute to the economy and to enhanced organizational performance. Burke and Cooper (2008) highlight a number of examples of management research that can positively influence organizational performance and the success of an economy. Sirota, Mischkind and Meltzer (2005) found that companies who have more enthusiastic and job-satisfied employees outperform the average stock market prices of other companies in their sector by more than two and a half times; and that companies with low job satisfaction and unenthusiastic employees lag behind their industry competitors' average price by five times. The authors found that the role of management was fundamental to levels of employee satisfaction and enthusiasm. Managers who engendered pride, camaraderie and equity among their employees produced the best performance. Leslie, Loch and Schaninger (2006) also explored the relationship of management practices in 230 businesses around the world, collecting data on more than 115,000 individual managers and employees. They concluded that three management practices were common among many of their high performing organizations: clarifying roles and accountabilities, articulating a compelling direction and vision for the future, and developing a strong performance-oriented culture based on openness and trust. Kotter (1996) and Kotter and Cohen's (2002) follow-up work found that successful management practices for large-scale change, in over 100 cases of major organizational restructurings, identified eight successful managerial behaviours: (1) increasing urgency for change among respected and influential employees; (2) building the guiding team for the change, those with credibility, skills and reputations; (3) creating the right vision; (4) communicating to all stakeholders for buy-in; (5) empowering all to action; (6) creating short-term wins; (7) being persistent, showing employees that the vision is being realized; and (8) perpetuating the change, making the new behaviours become part of the new culture. And finally, the notion that major structural change inevitably means downsizing and outsourcing was contradicted by Cascio's (2002) research involving an 18-year study of the Standard and Poor's 500 firms, showing that companies who restructured through downsizing were not only less profitable than those who did not, but tended to do far worse. Treating people as disposable assets, to exploit them when you need them but to dispense with them when you do not, has adverse consequences, not only to the health and self-esteem of individuals but also to the bottom line of the firm. All of these studies are examples of how management research can make a difference to the performance, productivity and well-being of organizations. This is evidence-based management, with a more focused purpose to provide the data and support organizations need, particularly during the onerous economic times we are going through. Weitzel (2009) sets the challenge for peak performing organizations in the future: unrelenting pressure for continuing change from technological innovation, and altered expectations of clients and customers, force high performance leaders to guide their organizations through each new set of pressures for change. High performance leaders recognize they must work with those they lead to make them part of the process, as origins and not pawns, from the earliest stages, through the planning for change and then through the completion to the next phase. The high performing organization operates as a team or set of teams. Clearly innovation and genius are important ingredients. But success in a high performance culture is the result of the actions of all. We, as management researchers, are part of that team, providing the ideas, evidence and good practice examples, as ammunition for change and development in the managerial and organizational arena – a challenge, never needed as much as in today's world of business. Cary L. Cooper, CBE, is Distinguished Professor of Organizational Psychology and Health at Lancaster University Management School, Chair of the Academy of Social Sciences and Founding President of the British Academy of Management.
