AB  - In order to understand the influences on firms' internationalization, it is necessary to consider non-market factors that cannot be easily calculated economically in addition to observable market factors.Even among firms with the same background and capabilities, the success of internationalization varies in various ways, and this study analyzes the impact of political relationships as a non-market factor on the internationalization of firms through an analysis of the political relationships of firms among the factors that affect the success of internationalization, and presents the results to contribute to relevant decision-making for the internationalization of firms.This study examines the impact of top management team political relationships on the internationalization of Chinese listed firms.The objective of the study is to identify the relationship between the political relationships of top management (the top decision makers of a company, whether formal or informal) and firm internationalization, which is one of the main determinants of the internationalization process.To this end, we selected a sample of beverage, computer, aircraft, toothpaste, pharmaceutical, book publishing, industrial banking, and credit card companies listed on the Shanghai and Shenzhen stock exchanges in China between 2010 and 2021, and used CSMAR, which contains financial statements of Chinese companies, as data to analyze the financial status of these companies.While previous studies on corporate internationalization have been based on economic factors, this study is different in that it focuses on a non-market factor, namely the political relationships of top management, and attempts to identify the relationship between the types of political relationships and internationalization, thereby identifying the mechanism between the types of political relationships and internationalization.In particular, in the process of testing a total of six hypotheses, this study drew different conclusions from the results of previous studies that political relationships of top management facilitate the internationalization of firms.The study is significant in that it empirically revealed the moderating effects of local and industry characteristics, and provided practical implications in that the internationalization process that relies on the political relationships of top management is not effective in terms of the internationalization performance of firms.
