AB  - China’s Belt and Road Initiative (BRI) has provided Chinese firms with significant incentives to speed up the pace of internationalization. Yet very little international business research has examined the policy effects. This study is among the first to examine this important issue using Chinese firms of different ethnicities (Uygur and Han) in the Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region (XUAR) of China. We propose that the BRI has a positive effect on the export performance of XUAR firms that target the “Belt” countries. Cultural friction and ethnicity moderate the relationship between the BRI and export performance in an opposite way. In particular, the BRI helps Uygur-owned firms more because of their inherent ethnicity advantage.
