AB  - The dominant perspectives in entry mode research such as the transaction costs perspective and Dunning’s OLI paradigm have come under criticism from researchers who recommend integrating efficiency considerations with behavioral/strategic considerations. This study responds to such calls for context-specific theory building by drawing upon inter-organizational imitation literature and anecdotal evidence of Indian firms. Specifically, we study the FDI-based market entry mode decisions of Indian MNEs to understand and explain how a firm’s likelihood of choosing a particular entry mode relates to its organizational form, investment motivations, international focus, industry patterns of internationalization and the level of economic development in host countries. We tested the hypotheses on a sample of 2244 international entries made by Indian firms between 2007 and 2013. The results indicate that entry mode choices are influenced by mimetic pressures operating at the industry and business group level. The mimetic pressures were significantly higher when firms entered developed markets and when firms internationalized to seek access to tangible and intangible assets. We did not, however, find support for the enhancement of financial performance of firms that chose entry modes by imitating their peers. We conclude this paper by accounting for this lack of support for financial performance, discuss the limitations of this study and suggest some directions along which future research can be carried out.
