AB  - The global economy has stumbled from one crisis to another — the dotcom crash to the sub-prime crash and now the Eurozone catastrophe, making the business landscape uncertain and therefore risky. It has resulted in strategic risk in the aftermath of acquisitions abroad recently by the Indian MNCs. Coping with such crises involves pain as business entities disrupt their schedules. Pain also seeps in through restructuring when the control levers, namely, action levers, context levers and system levers are in full play. There is also a shift from national to global markets that has intensified competitive rivalry in industry. In such a situation, it may not be possible to leverage skills and products associated with a firm’s distinct competencies from one market to another. It may also not be feasible and possible to serve the global market from a single low-cost location, thereby producing a globally standardized product, and then marketing it worldwide to achieve economies of scale, more so when the world economy is sluggish. Scale upon entry depends on the strategic commitment. The risks associated with commitments may diminish if a company acquires a host-country enterprise. Acquisitions, though, can raise a set of additional problems and these problems may offset the benefits. One significant feature of acquisitions is the painful exercise of setting the house in the order (in terms) of priorities, structures and processes. In a situation of meltdown or slowdown, firms are under increasing scrutiny for value creation and governance. So the roots of strategic pain can be found in strategy, management and financial well-being. Fundamental leverage points to effect transformation are cost reduction, asset reduction and restructuring. All operating units modify their behavior and routines in the desired manner in the transition period. In this paper, most firms and the Indian MNCs and conglomerates in particular are moving through the coping cycle of acquisitions and internationalization. Substantial changes come to control systems as managers begin to try and develop expectations of unit performance and work out on measures of performance.
