KW  - Active learning (machine learning)
AB  - This New Direction in Teaching and Learning journal volume is a continuation of conversations begun in issue Number 169 published in 2022 (Gillespie, A. R., Groccia, J. E., Mason, J. L. and Long, K. A.) and both volumes explore international perspectives on critical issues impacting teaching and learning in a diverse range of higher education environments. The 2022 volume presented 9 articles exploring issues related to understanding learning and teaching from multiple cultural, disciplinary, and institutional viewpoints. Both the past and present volumes represent efforts of the Auburn University Office of International Programs to expose higher education professionals (teachers, administrators, and students) to discussions begun during Auburn University's biennial International Perspectives on University Teaching and Learning Symposiums. Some of the articles in both volumes are extensions and elaborations of symposium presentations thereby providing presenters the opportunity to share their thoughts with a wider global audience. Other articles were accepted for publication after a careful review of manuscripts submitted following an international call for proposals. The goal of this volume is to transcend borders—institutional, disciplinary, and international—in order to expose higher education professionals to issues and concepts relevant to teaching and learning in an increasingly globalized world. Recognizing that faculty engage students from diverse backgrounds in their classrooms and that student success necessitates the pursuit of global literacy, the editors have selected articles addressing topics within both these spheres. Through this volume, the editors hope to spark further cross-border conversation around these ideas to encourage the development of creative approaches to internationalized teaching. The majority of the 13 articles in this volume have been written by authors from the US discussing efforts and curricular innovations to support the inclusion of global perspectives in higher education teaching and learning. However, the US voice is not exclusive as authors from Colombia, Armenia, Germany and Brazil have shared their perspectives to the discussion. Additionally, a number of articles have included data collected from students in Saudi Arabia, Brazil, Colombia, Canada, China, Estonia and Japan as well as the US, thereby contributing to and expanding the continuing conversations on the worldwide focus on university teaching and learning. The first Chapter in this volume, Becoming an Excellent Teacher: Suggestions from International Research Using the Teacher Behavior Checklist, written by William Buskist and James E. Groccia, presents a synthesis of research conducted over more than two decades to identify the essential behaviors and characteristics of excellent teachers. Research using the Teacher Behavior Checklist (TBC) has been conducted within a wide range of higher education institutions across the globe, leading to generalizable universal principles of teaching excellence that are transferable to academics in institutions worldwide. Using the TBC, international higher education researchers have identified five universal principles of excellent teaching: (1) teacher knowledge, (2) enthusiasm, (3) creativity and interestingness, (4) approachability and personability, and (5) effective communication. In this article, Buskist and Groccia describe each of these behaviors and offer suggestions for improving teaching by developing and refining each of these principles. In Chapter 2, How the Inclusion of International Perspectives Can Benefit Student Learning in Higher Education: Leadership Needs, Richard Collie and Catherine M. Wehlburg discuss how intentionally adding international students and faculty to a regional public university in the USA brings opportunities and challenges. The authors propose that the inclusion of non-US students and/or faculty provides new perspectives and brings diverse ideas and backgrounds to the forefront of education, not without difficulties that must be recognized and addressed. This article shares how a small, public university in the US South has worked to diversify its student body, faculty, and staff. In Teaching Quality Evaluation and Student Level of Moral Thinking: A Look Through the TBC and DIT Measures of Correlation, Chapter 3, Antonio César Donado and Carlos Enrique Zerpa summarize the statistics and findings from research to show the correlation between the Teachers Behavior Checklist (TBC) and the Defining Issue Test (DIT). To better understand the results of this comparison, the researchers decided to investigate the narrative of both instruments from a critical point of view because they implied similar levels of logical and critical thinking. In doing so, it was necessary to review the philosophical, psychological, and linguistic principles underlying this theory of discourse. Chapter 4, A Study on the Participation and Impact of Study Abroad for Undergraduate Students in a College of Architecture, Design and Construction by C. Ben Farrow, Eric M. Wetzel, Tom Leathem, Kendall McGoey investigates the participation of students in a study abroad program at College of Architecture, Design and Construction to better understand student participation and the perceived impact of study abroad experiences. Results indicate that students in the college participate in study abroad at a higher rate than other colleges in the university and cite this as a peak learning moment. These findings suggest that studying abroad can be a powerful transformational experience for graduating students in a College of Architecture, Design, and Construction. The study also provides valuable insights into the elements of high-impact educational practices and components of moments that can be incorporated into study abroad programs to maximize student learning and growth. In Chapter 5, 360° Immersive Video for Internationalizing Teaching and Learning: A Tool for Future Education Abroad, Andrew R. Gillespie and Harshil Goyal explore how 360° immersive video technology can revolutionize international teaching and learning, providing students with unparalleled virtual experiences that transcend geographical boundaries. The authors discuss why this tool is essential for future education abroad and how it can enrich global perspectives from the comfort of one's classroom. James E. Groccia in Chapter 6, Moving from Scholarly Teaching and Learning to the Scholarship of Teaching and Learning: A Global Imperative is a synthesis and elaboration suggesting that academic staff worldwide wishing to enhance teaching should first acknowledge and understand why quality teaching is critical for student improvement and institutional and community survival. He then recommends that academic staff develop an approach to teaching improvement that builds upon a firm foundation of scholarly teaching and learning. With this foundation, academic staff can develop a scholarship of teaching and learning to assess the impact of their teaching upon student learning, and subsequently to share their findings with colleagues, both within and outside their university to assist in future teaching and learning improvement. In Chapter 7, Worth a Thousand Words: Gaining Insight into Intercultural Learning through Photo Narration, Jacob Kelley and Laura Cruz provide examples of teaching, learning, and scholarship projects in which photo narration is used to document a myriad of learning outcomes—cultural humility, belonging, civic agency, and advocacy—that have relevance for integration in global education. Knar Khachatryan and Valentina Hartarska in Chapter 8, A Joint Assignment as a Simple and Effective Way to Connect Students from Different Countries, describes an experiment exploring efforts at the internationalization of research methods courses taught at Auburn University (AU) and American University in Armenia (AUA). Students from the US and Armenia were asked to complete a specially designed joint assignment that allowed them to engage in experiential learning. Results suggest that such assignments can effectively enhance students’ interest in research methods courses and improve their learning outcomes. In addition, they state that this approach demonstrates that efforts to internationalize higher education can be effective even in a singular course by course approach. Chapter 9, Disrupting Students' Learning Habitus: A Digitalized University Didactic Setting in Teacher Training by Gudrun Marci-Boehncke and Matthias O. Rath describes the implementation of “21st Century Skills” in a teaching/learning setting. The authors describe how students across disciplines and universities designed Massive Open Online Courses (MOOCs) didactically in digital learning spaces within a peer-to-peer approach. Karen McBride in Chapter10, Re-Imagining Sustainability in International Education: A New Narrative frames the emergence of environmental and social sustainability within international higher education, particularly study abroad programs, by exemplifying specific circumstances relating to the climate crisis, highlighting typical narratives by educators, and comprehensively analyzing the field's performance by two state-of-the-art surveys in 2021 and 2023. In Cognitive Skill Development to Support Biculturalism and Entrepreneurial Innovation, Chapter 11, Kim McManus explores how educators can use Experiential Learning methodologies with students in higher education to develop cognitive skills that facilitate biculturalism and innovation. McManus suggests that this approach is especially promising for business students who aspire to international experiences and entrepreneurial business ventures. Chapter 12, International Virtual Exchange and Field Trips: In an Introductory Environmental Science Course by Minory Nammouz suggests that incorporating global learning into college-level coursework can assist students in making connections between their studies and the world outside the classroom. Nammouz proposes that incorporating International Virtual Exchange (IVE) can provide students with a global classroom learning experience that helps overcome the financial or academic schedule constraints that prevent students from traveling abroad and participating in first-hand experiences with students from diverse cultures. In the final article in this volume, Chapter 13, Virtual Exchange as a Strategy to Foster Global Learning and Internationalization of the Curriculum, expands upon the topic presented in Chapter 12. Ana Cristina Biondo Salomão and José Celso Freire Junior describe the development of one of the first institutional initiatives for implementing a virtual exchange program in a university in Brazil. The focus is on the description and discussion of the role of stakeholders in fostering and supporting virtual exchange activities, as well as examples of implemented courses and an analysis of students’ perceptions of the practical issues associated with virtual exchange, its interface with employability and new skills and competences demanded by the labor market. The editors of this special topic issue of New Directions for Teaching and Learning hope that these 13 chapters add to the literature on international higher education in a way that stimulates future conversation, research, and efforts to support student and institutional success. It has been a pleasure working with these authors and we feel privileged to have been provided this opportunity to share their ideas and findings to the global community.
