AB  - India seemed to have all the right ingredients for growth: a well-educated population; the legacy of good British institutions (the English language, democracy, a strong legal tradition, bureaucracy, and Asia's oldest stock exchange); and geographical advantages (many ports and being located mid-way between East Asia and Europe). The large population was once considered to be a hindrance to growth, but now it provides the advantage of a large domestic market that would enable the reaping of scale economies. But for so long, India defied its destiny to become one of the growth centers in the world. Maybe this was because it adopted the wrong economic development model (socialistic planning), or maybe this was because of political inattention to the economy. Gradually, socialism was modified in the 1980s and later abandoned at around the same time the Berlin Wall fell. Growth rates since the 1990s have been remarkable. During the last 5 years, the average growth rate has accelerated to 8.5%, and the growth rate of per capita income has been 7% per annum. Is this at last the moment of takeoff of the giant economy into a high-growth orbit that many Asian countries, from Japan to South Korea, to Thailand, to China, have traveled before? What made this economic takeoff possible? What are the potential risks that lie ahead? These are the fundamental questions we had in mind when we started to plan this issue of the Asian Economic Policy Review. India has experienced a gradual increase in gross domestic product (GDP) growth rates. The average growth rate was 3% from the 1960s to 1980s, then it went up to 5% in the 1990s, and 8% after 2003. Many point to the role of reforms in the 1980s and 1990s in bringing about this growth acceleration. Some make a distinction between the two: the pro-business reforms in the 1980s, and the pro-market reforms in the 1990s (see Rodrick & Subramanian, 2005; Kochhar et al., 2006). Some find the process of growth acceleration puzzling. Why did growth not jump up to the 10% level upon the implementation of these reforms just like in China in the 1990s? However, we need to examine whether the reform was of the big bang type or just a series of small reforms, and how much the reforms would trigger a burst of business activity. Panagariya (2008; pp. 16–21) summarizes the debate over the relative roles of the reforms in the 1980s versus the reforms in the beginning of the 1990s. The mainstream view, which is also echoed in all the papers and the conference discussions in this issue, is that the reforms at the beginning of the 1990s are the crucial ones. Many emphasize that the reforms took place in several installments. This explains the gradual increase in the growth rates in the 1990s until recently. However, there are some critics in the literature. DeLong (2003) is skeptical of the defining role of the 1990s reform. He argues that the growth acceleration started in the early 1980s with some reforms, and that the reforms in the 1990s were just the second wave. DeLong (2003; p. 186) states that “in the absence of the second wave of reforms in the 1990s, it is unlikely that the rapid growth of the second half of the 1980s could be sustained. But hard evidence to support such a strong counterfactual judgment is lacking.”Rodrick and Subramanian (2005) suggest that an “attitudinal change” on the part of the government in favor of private businesses around 1980 may have been enough to ignite growth. In essence, a regime shift occurred when the government indicated pro-business attitudes in the 1980s rather than when the pro-market reforms were introduced in the 1990s. Rodrick and Subramanian (2005) argue that productivity surges occurred at around 1980, a decade earlier than is commonly believed, and that the trigger may have been the change in government attitudes toward the private sector. In short, the critics argue that the growth rate was already high toward the end of 1980s, so that reforms in the beginning of the 1990s should have only a limited role in the acceleration of the growth rate. Those who rebutted the critics include Srinivasan (2005) and Panagariya (2008). Both argue that the growth acceleration toward the end of the 1980s was of the type that would not be sustainable. Growth was stretched by fiscal stimulus financed by fiscal deficits. The high growth ended in the balance of payment crisis of 1990 and the crisis was the impetus for the 1991 reforms. They point out that the critics’ claim that growth in the 1990s was no higher than in the 1980s is wrong. It depends on whether or not the 1988–1991 period is included. Panagariya (2008; p. 17) argues that the “superhigh growth of 7.6% per annum during 1988–1991 was preceded by significant reforms, especially in the years 1985–1986 and 1986–1987. But in addition, this growth (as well as that during 1981–1988) was also driven by fiscal expansion and external borrowing that were not sustainable. Unsurprisingly, the surge ended in a macroeconomic crisis in June 1991.” Although the counterfactual of what would have been the outcome if the reforms of the early 1990s were not implemented is not directly testable, all the suggestive evidence in the papers collected in this issue lead us to believe that the reforms in the 1990s were significant and remarkable. However, it takes time for structural reform to bear fruit, and this would explain the gradually increasing growth rate. A separate issue is the role of financial markets for India's economic development, an issue that has been addressed by two recent working papers. Topalova (2008) undertakes an the states and the states that have experienced the relative for the have a higher of financial development, and a higher average In a (2008) that India's financial is not to with a high level of external financial and in that have a higher external financial are This summarizes the papers at the Asian Economic in on the by the and the of (2008) an of the that h